data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now accepts a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your expression-tree building code **won't compile** because `ExecuteUpdate` now takes `Func<...>` instead of `Expression<Func<...>>`. The fix is dramatically simpler:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

Delete all the `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` machinery.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Column uniquification:** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one column. EF 10 appends a number to disambiguate (e.g. `Street` and `Street1`). To preserve the old behavior, pin column names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path:** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to column `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

If you're creating a fresh database (no existing schema), the new defaults are fine and you can skip this.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)        // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update all other methods on the interface similarly (`CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandNonQueryExecuting`, and their `*Executed` counterparts).
